content.description: A shorty, but goody! I'd be surprised if I had an FA on this one because it was obvious, however it did require 20 minutes of scrubbing lichen to reveal the holds. Sit start with hands on opposite sides of large feature. Make big deadpoint to lip and top out.
content.protection: 1 pad (maybe 2 if you  want to pad the boulder to the right).
content.location: From the descent, head west. Probably close to directly below the east edge of the parking lot on the top of the cliff. Boulder faces south. North of a very large boulder.

content.description: Sit start with lowest left and right hand edges to the left of the arete. Left foot smear. Right heal hook around arete about right hand level. Pull to slanted edges and continue straight up to gain the slab..
content.location: Head south from the descent through the cliff line until the boulders start to peter out. Head west. This boulder faces south. It is east of a very large boulder and pretty obvious.

content.description: I doubt this was an FA because it was so obvious, but it did require a fair amount of cleaning. Stand start. Left hand on lowest positive edge, right hand on low undercling. Decent warm up.
content.location: From the descent through the cliff line, head south to where the boulders start to peter out, then head west. This is on the east face of a large boulder.

content.description: Although this problem is crazy short, the Elephant Trunk feature is super cool. I was happy to find it more difficult than it looked. Sit start, hand on opposite sides of the "Trunk" feature as low as possible.
content.location: From the descent through the cliff line, head straight downhill and traverse west. Located on southside of a short boulder.
